Author: soph0n
Content:
the exploration is the point, and as a consequence you will go outside of the order the developer intends (they are very much trying to invisibly guide you the whole way through). So my meaning is that when they fail at guiding you you will end up misunderstanding things or getting stuck or ruining some "aha" moments. One such example is accidentally dying at the fire, or accidentally leaving your lamp behind.

So yes, I think if you break the sequence (unintentionally) then you will have a slightly inferior experience overall. There is no solution to this problem, making it completely linear ruins the feeling of discovery.

Author: lattyware
Content: I disagree, because while it may mean you lose out on some particular aspects, if you achieve one of those, you get something more fun in terms of feeling smart for doing it, and it underscores the fact you *can* which makes other stuff feel more weighty and makes you interact more meaningfully. That trade off is worthwhile. If you skipped them *all* sure, that'd be worse, but the game is set up so most people are going to get one or two by luck, and the rest by exploring, which gives the best experience.

Author: lattyware
Content: So we've talked about "puzzle game" when it comes to Outer Wilds before, and I think it's a misleading way to label the game, because fundamentally the game is set up to have the answers in the game, and the player is meant to explore to find them. While these can be thought of, and even solved as, puzzles, if a player takes the view of treating it like a classic puzzle game like The Witness, solving each puzzle as they come to it, they'll have a bad time. The core of the game is exploration, and while it's fun and likely players will "solve" a few puzzles without finding answers by exploring, that isn't the core of the game.

Author: Deleted User
Content:
The game really has 3 very different approaches to things.
Hearthians are almost suicidally reckless but unafraid and bold. They make the best out of what they can find
Nomai are endlessly curious and approach things carefully and scientifically and manged to create technological marvels and explore even the most hostile of places.
The Owl people are the least concrete, they seem to be pretty cultured, smart, have important traditions and seem to be very spiritual / can learn things by just projecting mental images. But they are also the most afraid of progress and the inevitable.

Author: lattyware
Content:
Finishing the game again is worth doing.
- ||There is the tower puzzle you never did, that leads to stuff.||
- ||There is a third secret archive in the starlit cove.||
- ||There are sneaking routes to get into the starlit cove and endless canyon archives.||
- ||There is a contactless route to get into the endless canyon archive, without sneaking or using the glitch. (Also for starlit cove but timing is incredibly tight).||
- ||You can ask Hal to try and translate the language.||
- ||You can ride the wave on a raft.||
- ||You can see the dam only starts breaking when the solar sails open by putting your scout on it, it has surface integrity.||
- ||There is an uncensored version of the artifact testing reel if you stand on top of the lift at one of the archives.||

Author: lattyware
Content: All games trade away perfectly crafted experiences for player interaction. Outer Wilds specifically has this promise of things being logical and not locked by anything other than knowledge. The ability to discover or work things out is part of it, and even if a particular run is suboptimal in some way, any game that forces you onto an optimal path would be worse for it.

Content: To me, the uniqueness of the run, and the moments it produced were super interesting.

Author: lattyware
Content: The optimal route for an Outer Wilds run is probably to find one or two smaller skips spread out over the entire game so you feel smart and to reinforce the fact the world works like that and you can think about it that deeply, and to discover the rest via exploration, but I don't think skipping more makes anywhere nears as much of a negative difference as you are implying.

Author: lattyware
Content: but as I say, it depends on how you value these things

Content: so I don't think there is one true answer
